'''Barbara Ann Mandrell''' (born December 25, 1948)<ref name="PBS">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Ken |title=Barbara Mandrell Biography |url=https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/barbara-mandrell-biography/ |website=[[PBS]] |access-date=January 17, 2022}}</ref> is a retired American [[country music]] singer and musician. She is also credited as an actress and author. During the late 1970s and early 1980s, she was considered among country's most successful music artists. She had six number one singles and 25 top ten singles reach the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs|country songs]] chart.<ref name="Country Songs">{{cite magazine |title=Barbara Mandrell chart history (Country Songs) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/barbara-mandrell/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> She also hosted her own [[Barbara Mandrell & the Mandrell Sisters|prime–time television show]] in the early 1980s that featured music, dance numbers and comedy sketches. Mandrell also played a variety of musical instruments during her career that helped earn her a series of major–industry awards.

Mandrell was born in Texas and raised mostly in California. Mandrell is from a musical family; she played several instruments by the time she was a teenager. Her skills on the [[steel guitar]] were noticed by country music entertainers, who gave Mandrell the chance to perform in public at age 13. During this period she became a regular on the television program ''[[Town Hall Party]]''. She also performed as a musician when she toured in shows featuring [[Johnny Cash]] and [[Patsy Cline]]. Her family formed a band in her late teens which traveled overseas and entertained military bases. After marrying in 1967, Mandrell briefly retired, but was inspired to pursue a singing career after watching a performance of the ''[[Grand Ole Opry]]'' live at the [[Ryman Auditorium]]. In 1969, she signed her first recording contract with [[Columbia Records]]. She was inducted as a member of the Grand Ole Opry in 1972.

In the early 1970s, Mandrell recorded a number of [[Single (music)|singles]] that combined country influences with [[R&B music|R&B]]–[[Soul music|soul]]. Her singles frequently made their way onto the country charts. Her most successful singles of this period were "[[Tonight My Baby's Coming Home]]" (1971) and "[[The Midnight Oil (song)|The Midnight Oil]]" (1973). In 1975, she moved to [[ABC Records|ABC]]–[[Dot Records|Dot]] records and reached her commercial breakthrough with country–pop singles like "[[Sleeping Single in a Double Bed]]" (1978), "[[(If Loving You Is Wrong) I Don't Want to Be Right]]" (1979), "[[I Was Country When Country Wasn't Cool]]" (1981) and "[[One of a Kind Pair of Fools]]" (1983). She became a concert headliner and won several major music awards including the Entertainer of the Year accolade from the [[Country Music Association]] two years in a row.

Mandrell sustained serious head and leg injuries in a near-fatal car accident on September 11, 1984. She seriously considered retirement for a time. However, she returned to recording in 1985 and had several more top ten country singles including "[[Fast Lanes and Country Roads]]" (1985), "[[No One Mends a Broken Heart Like You]]" (1986), and "[[I Wish I Could Fall in Love Today]]" (1988). She resumed performing, touring, and began guest-starring in several television shows and numerous commercials. Mandrell appeared in several television films and shows during the late 1980s and 1990s like ''Burning Rage'' and ''[[Empty Nest]]''. She continued recording into the 1990s, releasing several albums for the [[Capitol Records|Capitol]] label including ''[[No Nonsense (album)|No Nonsense]]'' (1991). In 1997, Mandrell announced her retirement from performing and recording. She continued acting until 2000. In 2009, she was inducted into the [[Country Music Hall of Fame]] for her work in the industry.

==Early childhood==
Mandrell was born in [[Houston, Texas]], on [[Christmas Day]], 1948.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}}<ref name="Allmusic">{{cite web |last1=Ankeny |first1=Jason |title=Barbara Mandrell: Biography |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/barbara-mandrell-mn0000788569/biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> She is the eldest child born to parents Mary Ellen ([[née]] McGill; born 1931) and Irby Matthew Mandrell (October 11, 1924 &ndash; March 5, 2009).{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}}<ref name="Biography">{{cite web |title=Barbara Mandrell – Age, songs, & husband – Biography |url=https://www.biography.com/musician/barbara-mandrell |website=[[Biography (TV program)|Biography]] |access-date=January 21, 2022 |archive-date=July 3, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220703180734/https://www.biography.com/musician/barbara-mandrell |url-status=dead }}</ref> The family later moved to [[Corpus Christi, Texas]], where her father was a police officer and her mother was a music teacher. Mandrell's younger sisters [[Louise Mandrell|Louise]] and [[Irlene Mandrell|Irlene]], were born there.<ref name="Texas Monthly">{{cite journal |last1=McConnico |first1=Patricia |title=Barbara Mandrell Barbara Mandrell's Corpus Christi harmonies |journal=[[Texas Monthly]] |date=October 1999 |url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/articles/barbara-mandrell/ |access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> While in Corpus Christi, Mandrell got acquainted with music. She sang and played music regularly at home. She also recalled having a natural ear for hearing music. "I remember once I was at my cousins' home in Falfurrias. We were playing outside—and I'm talking this is when I'm a little girl—and we were singing, of all things, 'I've Been Working on the Railroad.' All of a sudden I started to hear harmony. I began to sing it, and I just thought, 'This is the neatest thing in the world,'" she told ''[[Texas Monthly]]''.<ref name="Texas Monthly"/>

In her early childhood, she began performing publicly. Her first recollection of performing in front people was at her family's church singing a rendition of the "Gospel Boogie".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339}} In addition to singing, Mandrell also learned several instruments as a small child. Mandrell's mother taught her how to play the [[accordion]] and read music before she entered into the first grade.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}}<ref name="Hall of Fame">{{cite web |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=Barbara Mandrell: Artist Bio |url=https://countrymusichalloffame.org/artist/barbara-mandrell/ |website=[[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]] |access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> When she was six years old, the family moved to [[Oceanside, California]].<ref name="Texas Monthly"/> Irby Mandrell opened his own music store.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=379}} In her elementary school years, she learned to play [[saxophone]] while a part of the school band.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> During the same period, she started taking lessons on the [[steel guitar]] from her father's friend Norman Hamlet. After a year of practice on the instrument, Irby Mandrell took his daughter to a music trade show in [[Chicago, Illinois]]. At the program, she performed on the steel guitar. She was heard by country performer [[Joe Maphis]] who would help launch Mandrell's early career as a musician.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=379}}

==Music career==
===1960–1968: Late childhood and teenage years as a steel guitarist===
In 1960, Joe Maphis brought eleven-year-old Mandrell onto his country music show in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. As part of Maphis's act, she performed the steel guitar.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> Maphis also helped her secure a regular spot on the country music California television program ''[[Town Hall Party]]''.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=379}}{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}} Feeling as if she was the only female musician, Mandrell discovered on ''Town Hall Party'' that other female instrumentalists also existed: "Men dominated the world of country music, but I looked around and discovered there were more women than you might have thought."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339}} On summers off from school, Mandrell routinely went back to Las Vegas to perform.<ref name="CMT Interview">{{cite news |title=20 Questions With Barbara Mandrell |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1543487/20-questions-with-barbara-mandrell/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104095507/http://www.cmt.com/news/1543487/20-questions-with-barbara-mandrell/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 4, 2015 |access-date=January 18, 2022 |work=[[Country Music Television]] |date=October 18, 2006}}</ref> In 1962, she toured country music shows with artists [[Johnny Cash]] and [[Patsy Cline]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339}} During the tour, 13-year old Mandrell shared hotel rooms with Cline since she was underage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Snapp |first1=Lauryn |title=Barbara Mandrell Remembers Having Slumber Parties With Patsy Cline |url=https://aftermidnite.iheart.com/content/2021-03-18-barbara-mandrell-remembers-having-slumber-parties-with-patsy-cline/ |website=[[iHeartRadio]] |access-date=January 21, 2022}}</ref> She also performed steel guitar for [[Red Foley]], [[Little Jimmy Dickens]] and [[Tex Ritter]].<ref name="CMT Interview"/>
[[File:Zumsteel.jpg|thumb|right|As a teenager, Mandrell became skilled at the [[steel guitar]] and often played background for several country music artists.|alt=A pedal steel guitar, with the word "Zumsteel" written on its side.]]

When she turned 14, her parents formed the Mandrell Family Band with Barbara on steel guitar, mother Mary on piano, and father Irby on lead vocals.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339}} They also hired two outside musicians including drummer Ken Dudney, whom Mandrell would later marry in 1967.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=279-280}} The Mandrell Family Band mostly played military bases around the United States and performed a variety of music including songs by [[The Beatles]]. While in the band, Mandrell also learned how to play [[banjo]] and [[bass guitar]].{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=279-280}}<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> Mandrell also engaged in other activities during her teenage years. In 1965, she was voted "Miss Oceanside California".<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Miss Oceanside Scholarship Pageant-April 14 |url=https://osidenews.com/2018/04/03/2018-miss-oceanside-scholarship-pageant-april-14/ |website=Oside News |date=April 3, 2018 |access-date=January 21, 2022 |archive-date=January 21, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220121043722/https://osidenews.com/2018/04/03/2018-miss-oceanside-scholarship-pageant-april-14/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> She participated in the marching band, chorus and student council. She eventually graduated from high school in 1967.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339}}

Shortly after high school graduation, Mandrell married Ken Dudney and chose to retire from performing to become a full-time housewife.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}}<ref name="Hall of Fame"/><ref name="Allmusic"/> Her last performance trip was to [[Vietnam]] where the Mandrell Family Band entertained the troops fighting in the [[Vietnam War]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339}} Upon returning, Mandrell found out that her husband had been sent temporarily overseas for his Navy pilot career. Feeling alone, Mandrell visited with her parents who had just moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. There, the family attended a performance at the ''[[Grand Ole Opry]]''.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=279-280}} While watching the show that evening, Mandrell realized that she still wanted to perform. "I wasn't cut out to be in the audience," she recalled in 2003.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}} With father Irby acting as her manager<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> she got the chance to play steel guitar on a show located in the [[Printer's Alley]] section of Nashville. In addition to the steel guitar, Mandrell also sang on several selections in the show.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}} Her skills as both a singer and musician caught the attention of six different record companies who offered her a recording contract. This included country music producer [[Billy Sherrill]], who was watching the performance. In 1969, Mandrell signed with Sherill's label [[Columbia Records]] as a recording artist.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}}<ref name="Allmusic"/>

===1969–1974: Singing transition and early success at Columbia Records===
Mandrell started her singing career by cutting covers of [[R&B music|R&B]]–[[Soul music|soul]] selections.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}}{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}} Her first Columbia single made America's ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs|country songs]] chart in 1969 called "[[I've Been Loving You Too Long|I've Been Loving You Too Long (To Stop Now)]]".<ref name="Billboard Songs">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2}}</ref> It was a cover of the [[Otis Redding]] original.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}}<ref name="Allmusic"/> It was followed by the Billy Sherrill-penned "[[Playin' Around with Love]]" (1970). It became her first song to reach the top 20, peaking at number 18 on the ''Billboard'' country chart.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> Her next singles were covers of [[Aretha Franklin]]'s "[[Do Right Woman, Do Right Man]]" and [[Roy Head]]'s "[[Treat Her Right (Roy Head song)|Treat Him Right]]".<ref name="Allmusic"/><ref name="Billboard R&B songs">{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |author-link=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=250}}</ref> In 1971, Mandrell's debut studio album was released through Columbia, also titled ''[[Treat Him Right]]''. The disc included her charting singles between 1969 and 1971, along with covers of songs by [[Ivory Joe Hunter]], [[Joe South]]  and others.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Treat Him Right'' (LP Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=[[Columbia Records]] |date=October 4, 1971 |id=30967}}</ref> Her early success garnered Mandrell the Top New Female Vocalist award from the [[Academy of Country Music]] in 1970<ref name="ACM">{{cite web |title=Academy of Country Music (Barbara Mandrell) |url=https://www.acmcountry.com/winners?awardTitle=barbara+mandrell&awardCategory=&awardYear=&actionButton=Submit |website=ACM Country |access-date=February 26, 2021}}</ref> and a membership to the ''[[Grand Ole Opry]]'' in 1972.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}}<ref name="Opry">{{cite web |title=Barbara Mandrell |url=https://www.opry.com/artists/barbara-mandrell/ |website=[[Grand Ole Opry]] |access-date=January 22, 2022}}</ref>

[[File:Barbara Mandrell--1974.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Barbara Mandrell, 1974.|alt=A bust of Barbara Mandrell, who is wearing a red sweater and smiling.]]
In 1971, Mandrell's single "[[Tonight My Baby's Coming Home]]" was her first to peak in the top ten of the ''Billboard'' country songs chart.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> It was followed in 1972 by a cover of [[Joe Tex]]'s "[[Show Me (Joe Tex song)|Show Me]]", which made the top 20 on the same chart.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/>{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}} At the same time, Mandrell started recording with country singer [[David Houston (singer)|David Houston]]. Several of their recordings were released as singles and made the country charts in the United States and Canada. Their first single "After Closing Time" reached number six on the ''Billboard'' country survey and number four on Canada's ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Country songs list.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs">{{cite web |title=Search results for "Barbara Mandrell" under Country Songs |url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/list.aspx?OCRText=Barbara+Mandrell&ChartEn=Country+Singles& |website=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] | date=July 17, 2013 |access-date=January 16, 2022}}</ref> Their duets made the charts several more times between 1970 and 1974, including "I Love You, I Love You" (1973), which climbed into the ''Billboard'' top ten as well.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> Their recordings were released on a studio album titled ''[[A Perfect Match (David Houston and Barbara Mandrell album)|A Perfect Match]]''.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}}

Critics and writers took notice of Mandrell's fusion of country music with R&B and soul. Author Kurt Wolff of ''Country Music: The Rough Guide'' described her early chart records as "colorful, spirited country soul". Wolff further explained, "The songs weren't exactly all roots and downhome twang, but they were certainly closer to the ground (and the soul) than any of her later, more suburban material."{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}} Mary A. Bufwack and [[Robert K. Oermann]] highlighted Mandrell's country–soul mix in their 2003 book: "[Mandrell's delivery] gives her vocals a hoarse, urgent quality that she put to good use on 'blue-eyed soul' versions of R&B songs," they noted.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}}

In reviewing a Columbia compilation, [[AllMusic]]'s Greg Adams stated that her early work was "some of the best recordings [Barbara Mandrell] ever made."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''Super Hits'': Barbara Mandrell: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/super-hits-mw0000025164 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=January 22, 2022}}</ref> Some critics found that Mandrell's Columbia material lacked individuality and at times seemed closer resemble that of other Columbia artists. "Sometimes, it seems as if Sherrill isn't quite sure what to do with Mandrell. He keeps her away from anything that could be construed as a good fit for [[Tammy Wynette]], and when the country does turn toward the straight-ahead, it's still soft; [[Merle Haggard]]'s 'Today I Started Loving You Again' doesn't carry resignation in Barbara's hands, only reassurance," [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] commented on one of her early LP's.<ref name="This Time">{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |title=''This Time I Almost Made It'': Barbara Mandrell: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/this-time-i-almost-made-it-mw0000964059 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=January 22, 2022}}</ref>

In 1973, Columbia issued what was considered Mandrell's breakthrough record,{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}} called "[[The Midnight Oil (song)|The Midnight Oil]]". The song told the story of a wife having an affair and lying to her husband about the situation.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}}{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}} The single became her second solo top ten hit, reaching number seven on the ''Billboard'' country chart and number five on the ''RPM'' country chart.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/> Its corresponding [[The Midnight Oil|studio album of the same name]] reached the number eight position on the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums|country LP]]'s chart.<ref name="Billboard Country Albums">{{cite magazine |title=Barbara Mandrell chart history (Country Albums) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/barbara-mandrell/chart-history/clp/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=January 22, 2022}}</ref> In 1974, she reached the top 20 on the country chart with "[[This Time I Almost Made It]]",<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> which followed a similar country–soul style as her previous material.<ref name="This Time"/> Mandrell later reflected to ''[[Biography (TV program)|Biography]]'' about the lack of confidence she felt showcased her Columbia material: "There have been many times when I thought other people might be better singers or better musicians or prettier than me, but then I would hear Daddy's voice telling me to never say never, and I would find a way to squeeze an extra inch or two out of what God had given me."<ref name="Biography"/> In 1975, she left Columbia's roster.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}}

===1975–1986: Country–pop crossover and career peak===
[[File:Barbara Mandrell--1977 (2).jpg|thumb|right|180px|Barbara Mandrell in ''Billboard'' magazine, 1977.|alt=Barbara Mandrell in a sparkling dress.]]
In 1975, Mandrell signed a recording contract with [[ABC Records|ABC]]–[[Dot Records|Dot]] (it was later bought by [[MCA Records]]). With producer [[Tom Collins (producer)|Tom Collins]], Mandrell incorporated a [[Pop music|pop]] production that broadened her appeal with listeners.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}}{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}} Her first ABC–Dot single was 1975's "[[Standing Room Only (Barbara Mandrell song)|Standing Room Only]]", which was her first top five ''Billboard'' country song.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/><ref name="Allmusic"/> It was followed by the top 20 songs "[[That's What Friends Are For (Barbara Mandrell song)|That's What Friends Are For]]" and "[[Midnight Angel (song)|Midnight Angel]]".<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> Collins also incorporated R&B elements into her repertoire, which further elevated her commercial success.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}} Her R&B covers of [[Denise LaSalle]]'s "[[Married But Not to Each Other]]" and [[Shirley Brown]]'s "[[Woman to Woman (Shirley Brown song)|Woman to Woman]]"<ref name="Billboard R&B songs"/> made the American and Canadian country song top five in 1977.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> "Woman to Woman" was also her first enter the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name="Hot 100">{{cite magazine |title=Barbara Mandrell chart history (Hot 100) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/barbara-mandrell/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> These recordings appeared on her [[Lovers, Friends and Strangers|sixth]] and [[Love's Ups and Downs|seventh]] studio albums, which were also issued in 1977.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Lovers, Friends and Strangers'' (LP Album Information) |journal=ABC Records/Dot Records |date=1977 |id=673}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Lovers, Friends and Strangers'' (LP Album Information) |journal=[[ABC Records]] |date=1977 |id=2098}}</ref>

Mandrell reached her commercial zenith in the late 1970s with songs about infidelity and cheating.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}}<ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=442-443}} In 1978, "[[Sleeping Single in a Double Bed]]" was her first single to reach the number one spot on the ''Billboard'' and ''RPM'' country charts.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/> It was followed in 1979 by a cover of [[Luther Ingram]]'s R&B hit "[[(If Loving You Is Wrong) I Don't Want to Be Right]]".<ref name="Billboard R&B songs"/> It also topped the North American country charts{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}} and crossed over into the top 40 of the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and Canadian pop songs chart.<ref name="RPM Top Songs">{{cite web |title=Search results for "Barbara Mandrell" under Top Singles |url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/list.aspx?OCRText=Barbara+Mandrell&ChartEn=Top+Singles& |website=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] | date=July 17, 2013 |access-date=January 16, 2022}}</ref><ref name="Hot 100"/> On ''Billboard'''s [[Adult contemporary (chart)|adult contemporary]] survey, the single reached the top ten.<ref name="Adult Contemporary">{{cite magazine |title=Barbara Mandrell chart history (Adult Contemporary songs) |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/barbara-mandrell/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> Both tracks appeared on Mandrell's top ten ''Billboard'' country album ''[[Moods (Barbara Mandrell album)|Moods]]'' (1978). Her 1979 album ''[[Just for the Record (Barbara Mandrell album)|Just for the Record]]'' was also a top ten ''Billboard'' LP.<ref name="Billboard Country Albums"/> ''Just for the Record'' spawned the country–pop crossover singles "[[Fooled by a Feeling]]" and "[[Years (song)|Years]]".<ref name="Hot 100"/><ref name="Adult Contemporary"/>

Now at her career peak, Mandrell became a headlining concert act.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280-281}} Her concert productions included choreography, costume changes and featured Mandrell on multiple musical instruments.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=341}} One of her headlining performances was turned into a cable television special called ''The Lady Is a Champ''.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=444}} She also appeared on national television programs{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280-281}} and won the [[Country Music Association]]'s 1979 Female Vocalist of the Year accolade.<ref name="CMA">{{cite web |title=CMA Awards Past Winners & Nominees (Barbara Mandrell) |url=https://cmaawards.com/past-winners-and-nominees/?appSession=872006I570PUP4I4S84930T27GBPG6SZ9P8DHL92IP00W45L010XJ4351QY5V4ZP8Z5IJ4ONWTFEC64767XAJT3D10B86RLCHV5E2QHN3A80X689PI57KBSJ140FL48I |website=CMA Awards |access-date=February 26, 2021}}</ref> Between 1980 and 1982, she and her siblings co-hosted the [[NBC]] television series ''Barbara Mandrell & the Mandrell Sisters''.<ref name="Allmusic"/> It helped Mandrell become the first performer to win back–to–back Entertainer of the Year awards from the Country Music Association in both 1980 and 1981.<ref name="CMA"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=341}} Mandrell's recordings continued having commercial success too. She had top ten country singles with 1980's "[[Crackers (song)|Crackers]]" and "[[The Best of Strangers]]".{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280-281}} In 1981, MCA issued her first [[Barbara Mandrell Live|live album]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Barbara Mandrell Live'' (Cassette Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=[[MCA Records]] |date=1981 |id=MCAC-1697}}</ref> which charted the ''Billboard'' country albums top five<ref name="Billboard Country Albums"/> and certified gold in sales from the United States.<ref name="RIAA">{{cite web |title=''Barbara Mandrell Live'' Gold & Platinum |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=Barbara+Mandrell&ti=Live&format=Album&type=#search_section |website=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> The disc included a track about staying close to country roots called "[[I Was Country When Country Wasn't Cool]]".{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}} Released as a single, it was her fourth number one song on the ''Billboard'' country chart.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/>

[[File:MandrellDo Rites86.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Mandrell (upper right) on tour with her band, 1986.|alt=Barbara Mandrell in the upper right corner of the picture. To her bottom and left are seven men.]]
Mandrell's commercial momentum continued through the early 1980s.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} Her twelfth studio album ''[[...In Black & White]]'' reached number seven on the country albums list. It was followed by her fourteenth studio record ''[[Spun Gold]]'' (1983), which climbed to number five on the same list.<ref name="Billboard Country Albums"/> Both discs spawned the number one singles "[['Till You're Gone]]" and "[[One of a Kind Pair of Fools]]". Also included were the top ten recordings "[[Operator, Long Distance Please]]" and "[[In Times Like These]]".<ref name="Billboard Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/> Mandrell's [[Clean Cut|1984 album]] was also a top ten ''Billboard'' disc<ref name="Billboard Country Albums"/> and featured the top five singles "[[Only a Lonely Heart Knows]]" and "[[Happy Birthday Dear Heartache]]".<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> Mandrell's popularity allowed her to record an album of [[gospel music]] in 1982 titled ''[[He Set My Life to Music]]''.<ref name="Gospel">{{cite magazine |title="He Set My Life to Music": Barbara Mandrell's First Gospel Album |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=October 2, 1982 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=giQEAAAAMBAJ&dq=barbara+mandrell+gospel+album+billboard&pg=PT43 |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> The project brought Mandrell her first [[Grammy Awards|Grammy]] awards.<ref name="Grammys">{{cite web |title=Barbara Mandrell - Artist - GRAMMYs |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/barbara-mandrell/15274 |website=GRAMMY |access-date=February 26, 2021 |date=November 23, 2020}}</ref> She also collaborated on several duets with [[Lee Greenwood]] in 1984.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=281}} The duets were issued on their 1984 studio album ''[[Meant for Each Other]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Greenwood |first1=Lee |last2=Mandrell |first2=Barbara |title=''Meant for Each Other'' (CD Information) |journal=[[MCA Records]] |date=1984 |id=MCAD-31231}}</ref> which featured the top five country single "[[To Me]]".<ref name="Billboard Songs"/>

Despite her popularity and commercial appeal, Mandrell's early–1980s music received mixed reviews. Writer Kurt Wolff found that her 1980s recordings exemplified "a weak attempt to maintain her roots" featuring "garnish productions" that went "head-first into schmaltz".{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}} In reviewing her 1983 album, critic Greg Adams commented, "''Spun Gold'' contains some bizarre collisions of country music's traditional working-class perspective with disco-era glitz."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''Spun Gold'': Barbara Mandrell: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/spun-gold-mw0000880490 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> Meanwhile, writers Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann described her early 1980s singles as "powerful heartache songs" whose themes centered around "enduring financial hardship" and "proud-to-be country anthem[s]".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}}

On September 11, 1984, Mandrell and her two oldest children were in Tennessee heading home from shopping when another driver crossed the center line and hit them head on. Mandrell suffered a broken femur, shattered ankle, injured knee and a concussion that left temporary brain damage. The driver of the other vehicle died. Mandrell's children survived with minor injuries. The crash caused Mandrell to endure numerous surgeries on her femur and ankle. This led to prolonged pain and depression.<ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=281}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} "I never thought I would ever sing again or be Barbara Mandrell again, or any of that," she later told [[CNN]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Encore Presentation: Country Music Superstars |url=http://www.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0512/31/lkl.01.html |access-date=January 24, 2022 |work=[[CNN]] |date=December 31, 2005}}</ref> She eventually returned to the recording studio in May 1985,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Beck |first1=Marilyn |title=BARBARBA MANDRELL IS BACK RECORDING |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-05-25-8502020769-story.html |access-date=January 24, 2022 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=May 25, 1985}}</ref> which resulted in the 1985 top ten country single "[[There's No Love in Tennessee]]". It appeared on Mandrell's ''[[Greatest Hits (Barbara Mandrell album)|Greatest Hits]]'' compilation, which was also issued in 1985.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=282}} She returned to the stage for the first time in 1986 at the [[Universal Amphitheatre|Los Angeles Universal Amphitheatre]], with [[Dolly Parton]] serving as her opening act.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} Her next studio album ''[[Get to the Heart]]'' (1985)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Get to the Heart'' (LP Album Information) |journal=[[MCA Records]] |date=1985 |id=5619}}</ref> spawned the top ten ''Billboard'' songs "[[Fast Lanes and Country Roads]]" and "[[Angel in Your Arms]]".<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> Her final album for MCA appeared in 1986 titled ''[[Moments (Barbara Mandrell album)|Moments]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Moments'' (LP Album Information) |journal=[[MCA Records]] |date=1986 |id=5769}}</ref> It spawned the top ten country song "[[No One Mends a Broken Heart Like You]]".<ref name="RPM Country Songs"/><ref name="Billboard Songs"/>

===1987–1997: Later recordings, career slow–down and retirement===
In 1987, Mandrell signed a new recording contract with [[EMI America Records|EMI America]]. Her first album with the label was the studio offering ''[[Sure Feels Good (album)|Sure Feels Good]]'' (1987).<ref name="On the Record">{{cite news |title=On the Record |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/09/04/On-The-Record/7978557726400/ |access-date=January 24, 2022 |work=[[United Press International]] |date=September 4, 1987}}</ref> The disc reached number 24 on the ''Billboard'' country albums survey.<ref name="Billboard Country Albums"/> [[United Press International]] positively commented that, "Mandrell should be proud of this effort which should put her back on top of the charts."<ref name="On the Record"/> Yet, of its three singles only "[[Child Support (song)|Child Support]]" reached the top 20 of the North American country charts.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/> Mandrell's future singles and albums reached progressively–lower chart positions as a new group of traditionally–oriented country artists began having more commercial success.<ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=444}} Yet, Mandrell continued touring and remained a popular concert attraction through the 1980s and 1990s.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=282}}{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=444}}

Mandrell signed with [[Capitol Records]] in late 1987.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} Her first Capitol single was a cover of [[Ray Price (musician)|Ray Price]]'s "[[I Wish I Could Fall in Love Today]]", which reached the top five of the American and Canadian singles charts.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/> It was included on her nineteenth studio disc ''[[I'll Be Your Jukebox Tonight]]'' (1988). The project featured a traditional country sound and included production credits for the first time from [[Fred Foster]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''I'll Be Your Jukebox Tonight'' (CD Liner Notes and Information) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=1988 |id=90416}}</ref> It also spawned the top 20 single "[[My Train of Thought]]" (1989) and the charting song "Mirror, Mirror". Both songs were her final singles to chart in the United States.<ref name="Billboard Songs"/> Mandrell remained with Capitol until 1991. Her next two Capitol discs were both issued in 1990: ''[[Morning Sun (album)|Morning Sun]]''<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Morning Sun'' (CD Liner Notes and Information) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=1990 |id=C2-91977}}</ref> and ''[[No Nonsense (album)|No Nonsense]]'' (distributed through [[Liberty Records|Liberty]]).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''No Nonsense'' (CD Liner Notes and Information) |journal=[[Liberty Records]] |date=1990 |id=94426}}</ref> For the latter album, Mandrell signed a commercial deal with the [[Kayser-Roth|No Nonsense panty hose]] brand.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} Her final Capitol–Liberty project was issued in 1991 called ''[[Key's in the Mailbox]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Key's in the Mailbox'' (CD Liner Notes and Information) |journal=[[Liberty Records]] |date=1991 |id=C2-96794}}</ref> Mandrell's Capitol recordings found positive reviews from critics. Mary. A Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann found the songs to showcase "strong female lyrics",{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} while Bill Carpenter said her 1991 album exemplified "Heartful soul and contemporary country."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carpenter |first1=Bill |title=''Key's in the Mailbox'': Barbara Mandrell |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-keys-in-the-mailbox-mw0000268825 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref>

Mandrell continued making live performance appearances on network television. She also remained a popular act on the ''Grand Ole Opry'', including their televised portion of the program.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=282}} Mandrell also continued recording and releasing new material. In 1994, the New York label Direct Records released two albums of her music. The studio album projects were marketed exclusively through television and appeared on networks such as [[The Nashville Network|TNN]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Morris |first1=Edward |title=Nashville Scene |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=April 16, 1994 |page=38 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QggEAAAAMBAJ&dq=barbara+mandrell+billboard+1994&pg=PA38 |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> That year, the label issued ''[[Acoustic Attitude]]'', which was an album of [[Re-recording (music)|re-recordings]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''Acoustic Attitude'' (CD Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=Direct Records |date=1994 |id=DRD-002}}</ref> The label also issued an album of new material that year titled ''[[It Works for Me]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''It Works for Me'' (CD Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=Direct Records |date=1994 |id=DRD-004}}</ref> The album was reissued on [[Razor & Tie]] in 1997, which Mandrell temporarily signed a contract with that year.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |title=''It Works for Me'' (CD Liner Notes and Album Information) |journal=[[Razor & Tie]] |date=1997 |id=RT-2828-2}}</ref>

Also in 1997, Mandrell announced her retirement from touring, recording and performing. In an interview with ''Billboard'', Mandrell explained that she chose to retire so she could focus on a full–time acting career. She gave her final musical performance in October 1997 at the Grand Ole Opry house. Her final concert was aired on network television.<ref name="Retire">{{cite magazine |last1=Flippo |first1=Chet |title=Mandrell Readies Her 'Last Dance' |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=October 25, 1997 |page=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0wkEAAAAMBAJ&dq=barbara+mandrell+1988+billboard&pg=PA54-IA3 |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref> Titled ''Barbara Mandrell and the Do-Rites: The Last Dance'', premiered on TNN in late 1997.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/><ref name="Biography"/> After her retirement, Mandrell sold all of her musical instruments. She now spends time on her family and domestic responsibilities.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dukes |first1=Billy |title=The Secret History of Why Barbara Mandrell Seemingly Vanished |url=https://tasteofcountry.com/why-barbara-mandrell-vanished-secret-history/ |website=[[Taste of Country]] |access-date=January 24, 2022}}</ref>

==Acting career==
===1978–1983: Early roles and television variety series===
Mandrell began gaining regular exposure on national television programs.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280-281}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=341-343}} Her television credits from this period included appearances on ''[[The Tonight Show]]'', ''[[American Bandstand]]'' and [[Bob Hope]] entertainment specials.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280}} Among the highlights was an appearance on a 1979 episode of ''[[The Rockford Files]]''<ref name="Rockford">{{cite web |last1=Erickson |first1=Hal |title=''The Rockford Files: Love Is the Word'': Synoposis |url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-rockford-files--love-is-the-word-v429670 |website=[[AllMovie]] |access-date=January 29, 2022}}</ref> and co-hosting the 1979 [[Academy of Country Music Awards]].{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280-281}} In late 1979 she played Emmy in the holiday program ''Skinflint: A Christmas Carol'' alongside several other country artists of the era. The special was a southern American take on the [[A Christmas Carol|original story of the same name]]. Fred Guida gave the program a negative review in his book ''A Christmas Carol and Its Adaptations'': "Unfortunately, ''Skinflint'' fails to live up to its interesting premise, and the result is one of the lamest ''Carol'' variations to date."<ref>{{cite book |last1=Guida |first1=Fred |title=A Christmas Carol and Its Adaptations A Critical Examination of Dickens's Story and Its Productions on Screen and Television |date=2006 |publisher=McFarland, Incorporated Publishers |isbn=9780786428403 |page=205}}</ref>

Mandrell was given multiple offers from the [[NBC]] network to host her own syndicated show. However, she routinely turned it down. One day, NBC producer [[Sid and Marty Krofft|Marty Krofft]] was shown a wallet-sized photograph of Mandrell and her sisters playing different musical instruments. This prompted Krofft to contact Mandrell about offering her a program that she could co–host with her sisters. From his encouragement, she eventually agreed to host a show on his network.<ref name="Harrington">{{cite news |last1=Harrington |first1=Richard |title=Barbara Mandrell |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1982/08/13/barbara-mandrell/25e99f61-d3fb-4275-bc32-bd3866d8fc79/ |access-date=January 30, 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=August 13, 1982}}</ref> In 1980, she was signed by NBC to host a national television variety series. Titled ''[[Barbara Mandrell & the Mandrell Sisters]]'', the show was hosted by Mandrell along with her two sisters Irlene and Louise.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=280-281}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=341}}

Mandrell learned choreography for the show and was routinely featured playing multiple musical instruments.<ref name="Encyclopedia of Country Music">{{cite book |last1=Kingsbury |first1=Paul |last2=McCall |first2=Michael |last3=Rumble |first3=John |title=The Encyclopedia of Country Music The Ultimate Guide to the Music |date=1998 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199770557 |page=324}}</ref> In addition, the Mandrell sisters performed a series of comedy sketches. In their book ''The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows'', authors Tim Brooks and Earle F. Marsh noted that Barbara often portrayed the "serious, pushy sister" while Irlene was portrayed as the "sexy, vain one".<ref name="Prime Time">{{cite book |last1=Brooks |first1=Tim |last2=Marsh |first2=Earle F. |title=The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, 1946-Present |date=2009 |publisher=Random House Publishing Group |isbn=9780307483201}}</ref> Mandrell often had to push back against NBC executives who insisted that the show feature hay barrels and other features of traditional country-western shows. "They expect you to be barefoot and ignorant," Mandrell commented in 2003.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=341}} During its peak, it was estimated that the show attracted roughly 40 million viewers per week.<ref name="Encyclopedia of Country Music"/> For her work, Mandrell was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress – Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actress in a Television Musical or Comedy Series]] by the [[Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Barbara Mandrell: Golden Globes |url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/person/barbara-mandrell |website=[[Golden Globe Awards]] |access-date=January 29, 2022}}</ref>

[[File:Brooke Shields, Bob Hope and Barbara Mandrell.JPEG|thumb|right|250px|Mandrell continued entertaining into the late 1980s. Here, she appears with [[Bob Hope]] (center) and [[Brooke Shields]] (left) for a military engagement (1987).|alt=Comedian Bob Hope in the center. Singer Barbara Mandrell is kissing his left cheek, while actress Brooke Shields is stroking his right cheek.]]
Despite the NBC show's success, the constant workload (along with a focus on her music career) caused Mandrell to suffer from [[Occupational burnout|burnout]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339-341}}{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=442-443}} She often had to take extra naps on her tour bus parked next to the television studio. She also had to take [[Cortisone]] shots before show tapings so that her vocal chords had less strain.<ref name="Tennessean">{{cite news |last1=Schmitt |first1=Brad |title=Barbara Mandrell, her sisters to reunite for fur babies |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/life/2015/01/29/mandrell-sisters/22370355/ |access-date=January 29, 2022 |work=[[The Tennessean]]}}</ref> She was urged to quit the show by physicians who warned that she would ultimately suffer from permanent vocal damage.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=341}}<ref name="Tennessean"/> In 1982, Mandrell announced the program would end after a two-year run on NBC.<ref name="Prime Time"/> "I'm the only person that I know of that has ever left a television series with a five year contract," she later commented.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=341}}

===1984–2000: Later television roles===
Mandrell continued acting following her show's cancellation. In 1984, Mandrell debuted in her first [[television film]] titled ''Burning Rage''.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} Mandrell played the main role of a [[geologist]] who investigates coal mining fires underneath a town in Tennessee.<ref name="Burning Rage">{{cite web |title=''Burning Rage'' (1984) |url=https://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/461413/burning-rage#synopsis |website=[[Turner Classic Movies]] |access-date=January 29, 2022}}</ref> Joe Brown of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called the film, "an overheated title for what amounts to a lukewarm drama about a natural phenomenon and its effect on a small town." He concluded by commenting on Mandrell's acting performance: "As an actress, Mandrell is likable and natural, but she has little to do here but walk around looking concerned when she's not getting into tepid clinches with [Tom] Wopat".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Joe |title='Rage': Coal-Fired Clinker |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1984/09/21/rage-coal-fired-clinker/3a48c3ce-8c00-4155-a1f9-72fd8a294910/ |access-date=January 29, 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 21, 1984}}</ref> Following her 1984 car crash, a television special of Mandrell's was aired on [[CBS]] titled ''Barbara Mandrell–Something Special''.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=282}}

She also made appearances on talk shows and network programs during the late 1980s and early 1990s. She also was featured in several television commercials for food products.{{sfn|Stambler|Landon|2000|p=282}} In the early 1990s, she portrayed a character on the television show ''[[Empty Nest]]''.<ref name="Empty Nest">{{cite web |title=''Empty Nest'': Golden Globes |url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/tv-show/empty-nest |website=[[Golden Globe Awards]] |access-date=January 29, 2022}}</ref> In 1994, Mandrell played a villain guest role in an episode of ABC's ''[[The Commish]]''. ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'' described her as playing "a less sympathetic role than usual" in their description of the episode.<ref name="Commish">{{cite news |last1=Bianculli |first1=David |title=R.E.M. on 'SNL': reason to lose sleep |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1994-11-12-1994316043-story.html |access-date=January 29, 2022 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=November 12, 1994}}</ref>

During the mid 1990s, Mandrell also played roles on the shows ''[[Touched by an Angel]]'', ''[[Dr. Quinn Medicine Woman]]'' and ''[[Baywatch]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=GOODBYE, MUSIC....HELLO, ACTING |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1997-10-25-9711180042-story.html |access-date=January 29, 2022 |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |date=October 25, 1997}}</ref> In 1997, Mandrell gave up her music career to focus on acting full-time.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=444}} She signed with the Creative Artists Agency, which helped her acquire more television roles. She appeared as a recurring character in the soap opera ''[[Sunset Beach (TV series)|Sunset Beach]]''.<ref name="Retire"/> In 1999, Mandrell played the mother of a deceased son who finds conflict with his "controlling girlfriend". Titled ''[[The Wrong Girl (film)|The Wrong Girl]]'', the television filmed aired on NBC that year.<ref name="Wrong Girl">{{cite book |last1=Marill |first1=Alvin H. |title=Movies Made for Television, 1964-2004: 1990-1999 |date=2005 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=978-0810851740 |page=580}}</ref> Among Mandrell's final acting credits was 2000's made for television film ''Stolen from the Heart''.<ref name="Stolen">{{cite web |title=''Stolen from the Heart'' (2000) |url=https://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/478918/stolen-from-the-heart#credits |website=[[Turner Classic Movies]] |access-date=January 29, 2022}}</ref>

==Artistry==
===Musicianship===
In addition to singing, Mandrell is also known for playing multiple instruments.<ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=442-444}} In her teenage years, she was nicknamed "The Princess of Steel" for become a skillful steel guitar player.<ref name="PBS"/>{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=442}} In a 2006 interview with CMT, Mandrell explained that she is "proficient" on the steel guitar, [[alto saxophone]], [[dobro]], [[Banjo|five-string banjo]], and [[Bass (instrument)|bass]]. She also said that she can play the guitar and mandolin "if necessary".<ref name="CMT Interview"/> [[PBS]] described Mandrell as "a true prodigy" in reference to her musicianship.<ref name="PBS"/> ''[[News & Record]]'' found that Mandrell's musicianship can also be found in her live shows: "Those hours are packed with aerobics, as Mandrell dances and prances across the stage, playing several musical instruments and clowning with her Do-Rites band."<ref>{{cite news |title=BARBARA MANDRELL KICKS UP HER HEELS |url=https://greensboro.com/barbara-mandrell-kicks-up-her-heels/article_d74bddbb-3554-5889-beb9-18c66bf645ab.html |access-date=January 30, 2022 |work=[[News & Record]] |date=June 10, 1995}}</ref> In reviewing a concert, ''[[The Morning Call]]'' explained, "No Mandrell show would be complete without a demonstration of the singer's musical virtuosity. Playing a mean saxophone and banjo during the course of the evening, Mandrell proved herself to be a talented musician."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Longsdorf |first1=Amy |title=BARBARA MANDRELL NEEDS TO SHED FLASH AND FOCUS ON POWERFUL VOICE CONCERT REVIEW |url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1987-12-12-2598771-story.html |access-date=January 30, 2022 |work=[[The Morning Call]] |date=December 12, 1987}}</ref>

===Musical styles===
Mandrell's musical style embeds country music with country–pop,<ref name="Allmusic"/><ref name="PBS"/> R&B–soul,<ref name="Rolling Stone">{{cite magazine |last1=Kelly |first1=Hunter |title=How Barbara Mandrell's 1978 Hit 'Sleeping Single in a Double Bed' Got a Dance Remix |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=May 27, 2020 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/barbara-mandrell-sleeping-single-dance-remix-1005597/ |access-date=January 30, 2022}}</ref> and gospel.<ref name="Gospel"/> Jason Ankeny of AllMusic found that the most popular era of her career (late 1970s and early 1980s) had a "glitzier, more pop-influenced" sound.<ref name="Allmusic"/> Kurt Wolff highlighted a similar theme in his book ''Country Music: The Rough Guide'': "[Tom] Collins churned out frightfully slick and garnish productions, but Mandrell thrived in her new environment."{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}} Hunter Kelly of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' explained that when Mandrell began incorporating R&B sounds into her style that her career "really kicked into overdrive". Mandrell further explained her reasoning behind incorporating R&B: "To me, country music and R&B music have a lot of similarities, but the one thing that I think is the most important is both genres, just straight ahead, they're telling you. They're not making up a story just because it rhymes nicely."<ref name="Rolling Stone"/>
[[File:Barbara Mandrell DN-ST-87-03190.JPEG|thumb|right|200px|Mandrell was known for playing multiple musical instruments in her live shows. Here, she is seen playing the banjo, 1986.|alt=Barbara Mandrell, singing into a microphone while playing a banjo.]]

Writers found that Mandrell had her greatest commercial success with songs that incorporated subjects of cheating. Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann found this to be especially evident after she transitioned to her second record label: "Barbara continued to smolder in sin after moving to the ABC/MCA Records fold in 1975."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}} Kurt Wolff found a similar theme with cheating material: "The subjects of many of Mandrell's songs were also racy for the time, dealing openly with such topics as lust, sexual loneliness, and late night-night love trysts." Wolff further commented, "What's ironic about her subject matter is that Mandrell herself–a devout Christian, mother and wife– always maintained an impeccably clean, family–oriented profile."{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=443}} "I've recorded a lot of cheating songs, but there were a lot of cheating songs I turned down. It depends on the lyrics...God loves prostitutes too," Mandrell further commented.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}}

===Voice===
Mandrell's singing voice has also been the subject of discussion amongst writers and critics. Mary Bufwack and Robert Oermann commented that her habit of smoking cigarettes made her voice stand out: "Barbara is a heavy smoker, and this gives her vocals a hoarse, urgent quality that she put to good use on 'blue-eyed soul' versions of R&B songs," they commented in 2003.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}} In 1982, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' highlighted Mandrell's singing in a review of her concert performance: "At other times the gritty edges of her husky voice crackled with R&B flourishes and gospel fervor. It was an impressive display."<ref name="Harrington"/> In 1984, ''[[The Oklahoman]]'' commented on her live singing as well: "She can perform almost anything short of grand opera in fact, if she took a mind to, she probably could do that too (after all, Linda Ronstadt did!)."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hammett |first1=Kate |title=Mandrell concert awesome |url=https://www.oklahoman.com/story/news/1984/01/26/mandrell-concert-awesome/62816028007/ |access-date=January 30, 2022 |work=[[The Oklahoman]]}}</ref>

==Legacy, influence and honors==
Mandrell has been widely considered among country music's most successful artists and all–around entertainers.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=338-341}}<ref name="PBS"/><ref name="Allmusic"/> "Perhaps the toughest soldier in the female army that invaded the country charts in the 1970s, Barbara could outwork, outperform, out-talk, and out-smile virtually anyone in show business," wrote Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=338}} Jason Ankeny of AllMusic commented in a similar fashion: "Thanks to a string of hit singles and a popular television variety series, vocalist Barbara Mandrell was arguably the biggest female star in country music in the late '70s and early '80s."<ref name="Allmusic"/> Paul Kingsbury, Michael McCall and John Rumble explained that Mandrell, "took her soul–country style to the biggest showrooms of Las Vegas, ruled the country charts during the late 1970s and early 1980s, starred on network TV, and told her story in one of country's best–selling autobiographies".<ref name="Encyclopedia of Country Music"/>
[[File:President Ronald Reagan shaking hands with singer Barbara Mandrell.jpg|thumb|left|200px|President [[Ronald Reagan]] shakes hands with Mandrell at [[The White House]], 1986.|alt=Barbara Mandrell shaking hands with President Ronald Reagan.]]

Her influence on future artists has also shaped her legacy. Mandrell has been credited as an influence for [[Terri Clark]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bonaguro |first1=Alyssa |title=Terri Clark Gets an Old-School Thank You Note from Barbara Mandrell |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1825789/terri-clark-gets-an-old-school-thank-you-note-from-barbara-mandrell/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201009001340/http://www.cmt.com/news/1825789/terri-clark-gets-an-old-school-thank-you-note-from-barbara-mandrell/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 9, 2020 |access-date=February 5, 2022 |work=[[Country Music Television]] |date=October 8, 2020}}</ref> [[Reba McEntire]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Gayle |title=Reba McEntire Reflects on the Inspiration of Loretta Lynn, Dolly Parton and Others |url=https://popculture.com/country-music/news/reba-mcentire-reflects-inspiration-loretta-lynn-dolly-parton-more/ |website=popculture. |access-date=February 5, 2022}}</ref> and [[Carly Pearce]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Black |first1=Lauren Jo |title=Carly Pearce Shares Songs That Inspired 'Next Girl' In Exclusive Playlist Takeover |url=https://countrynow.com/carly-pearce-shares-songs-that-inspired-next-girl-in-exclusive-playlist-takeover/ |website=Country Now |date=September 20, 2020 |access-date=February 5, 2022}}</ref> McEntire thanked Mandrell in 2009 and spoke about her influence: "I thank you for the things that you've taught me, not only musically, but spiritually...And I will always treasure our relationship with all my heart."<ref name="CMT 2009">{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Edward |title=Barbara Mandrell, Roy Clark, Charlie McCoy Join Country Music Hall of Fame |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1611646/barbara-mandrell-roy-clark-charlie-mccoy-join-country-music-hall-of-fame/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129100456/http://www.cmt.com/news/1611646/barbara-mandrell-roy-clark-charlie-mccoy-join-country-music-hall-of-fame/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 29, 2015 |access-date=February 5, 2022 |work=[[Country Music Television]] |date=May 18, 2009}}</ref> In 2006, several artists re-recorded several of Mandrell's most popular singles in tribute to her career. The project was titled ''She Was Country When Country Wasn't Cool: A Tribute to Barbara Mandrell''. It featured of remakes of her songs performed by contemporary country performers such was [[Kenny Chesney]], [[Sara Evans]] and [[LeAnn Rimes]].<ref name="CMT Interview"/>

Mandrell has been only one of a few women to win the Country Music Association's Entertainer of the Year award, and one of only two women (alongside [[Taylor Swift]]) to win the award twice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vinson |first1=Christina |title=Every CMA Awards Entertainer of the Year Winner Ever |url=https://theboot.com/cma-awards-entertainer-of-the-year-winners/ |website=The Boot |access-date=February 5, 2022}}</ref> She was also the first individual to win the accolade in back to back years (1980 and 1981).<ref name="CMA"/><ref name="PBS"/> 
In 2005, she received the Triple Crown accolade from the Academy of Country Music for winning three major awards from the association. She is only one of several people to have since won the award.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Betts |first1=Stephen L. |title=Luke Bryan, Maren Morris to Perform at 2016 ACM Honors |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=August 10, 2016 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/luke-bryan-maren-morris-to-perform-at-2016-acm-honors-248085/ |access-date=February 5, 2022}}</ref> In 2009, Mandrell was inducted into the [[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]].<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> She was inducted that year along with [[Roy Clark]] and [[Charlie McCoy]].<ref name="CMT 2009"/> Her induction was celebrated that year at the Country Music Association Awards where Mandrell gave a speech to thank the industry.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shelburne |first1=Craig |title=Barbara Mandrell Praises Contemporary Country Music |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1626490/barbara-mandrell-praises-contemporary-country-music/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824163341/http://www.cmt.com/news/1626490/barbara-mandrell-praises-contemporary-country-music/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 24, 2017 |access-date=February 5, 2022 |work=[[Country Music Television]] |date=November 17, 2009}}</ref>

Mandrell's legacy was further cemented she released her 1990 [[autobiography]] called ''[[Get to the Heart: My Story]]'' (co-written with writer [[George Vecsey]] titled).<ref name="Orlando">{{cite news |last1=Hurst |first1=Jack |title=BARBARA MANDRELL'S LIFE: TRANSFORMED BY NEAR-DEATH |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1990-09-28-9009270426-story.html |access-date=January 29, 2022 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 28, 1990}}</ref> In 1997, the book was turned into a television movie titled ''[[Get to the Heart: The Barbara Mandrell Story]]''. She was portrayed in the film by television actress [[Maureen McCormick]]. Mandrell briefly made a cameo appearance at the beginning and end of the film.<ref name="AP">{{cite news |last1=Patterson |first1=Jim |title=Barbara Mandrell bets her career on television |url=https://apnews.com/article/a5cdef7795caee563adfa1be7f31ed22 |access-date=February 5, 2022 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 26, 1997}}</ref>

In 2020, American [[disc jockey]] and producer [[Dave Audé]] partnered with Mandrell to remix her 1978 song "Sleeping Single in a Double Bed". ''Rolling Stone'' explained that the song was remixed as "the first step in a new effort to bring Barbara Mandrell's music into the digital age."<ref name="Rolling Stone"/> It was followed by all of Mandrell's LP's being reissued to digital and streaming sites. Her original Columbia, ABC–Dot, MCA, and Capitol albums were all re–released through various digital platforms.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Hollabaugh |first1=Lorie |title=Barbara Mandrell Releases New Remix, Vinyl Album Collection |magazine=Music Row |date=June 1, 2020 |url=https://musicrow.com/2020/06/barbara-mandrell-releases-new-remix-vinyl-album-collection/ |access-date=February 5, 2022}}</ref>

In July 2022, Mandrell celebrated 50 years as a member of the Grand Ole Opry. Several Opry members and country artists performed on the stage to honor Mandrell's legacy. Among the artists who performed that night were [[Suzy Bogguss]], [[Jeannie Seely]] and [[Carrie Underwood]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goldstein |first1=Tiffany |title=Carrie Underwood Helps Barbara Mandrell Celebrate Her 50th Grand Ole Opry Anniversary |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1848521/carrie-underwood-helps-barbara-mandrell-celebrate-her-50th-grand-ole-opry-anniversary/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220801190317/http://www.cmt.com/news/1848521/carrie-underwood-helps-barbara-mandrell-celebrate-her-50th-grand-ole-opry-anniversary/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 1, 2022 |access-date=August 3, 2022 |work=[[Country Music Television]] |date=August 1, 2022}}</ref>

==Personal life==
===Marriage and family life===
Mandrell has been married to former musician and [[Navy]] pilot Ken Dudney since 1967.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339}}<ref name="Morning Call">{{cite news |last1=Willistein |first1=Paul |title=Barbara Mandrell just wasn't cut out to be in the audience|url=https://www.mcall.com/news/mc-xpm-1984-08-31-2429705-story.html |access-date=January 17, 2022 |work=[[The Morning Call]] |date=August 31, 1984}}</ref> Dudney was originally hired as the drummer for Mandrell's family band.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339}} The pair met when she was 14 and he was 21. Dudney was engaged to another woman at the time. However, he broke off the engagement after having feelings for Mandrell.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Falk |first1=Fredrik |title=Barbara Mandrell met her husband when she was just 14: Now shares the secret to their happy and lasting relationship |url=https://en.newsner.com/news/barbara-mandrell-met-her-husband-when-she-was-just-14-now-shares-the-secret-to-their-happy-and-lasting-relationship/ |website=Newsner |date=July 22, 2020 |access-date=January 17, 2022}}</ref> In 2003, Mandrell commented: "I'd dated him since I was 14 and I just couldn't wait to graduate high school so I could be Mrs. Ken Dudney."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=339-340}}<ref name="Morning Call"/> 

At the time of their marriage, Dudney gave up his career as a Navy pilot to help further his wife's career.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=340}} The couple welcomed their first child, Matthew, in 1970, followed by daughter Jaime in 1976.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=341}} In 1985 Mandrell gave birth to her third child, Nathan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandrell's 3rd Child Is a Boy |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1985-09-06-mn-23675-story.html |access-date=January 17, 2022 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 6, 1985}}</ref>

In 1988, Mandrell and her family built a log cabin mansion called the [[Fontanel Mansion]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kazek |first1=Kelly |title=Barbara Mandrell's former log mansion is now one of the area's biggest tourist draws |url=https://www.southernthing.com/barbara-mandrells-former-log-mansion-is-now-one-of-the-areas-biggest-tourist-draws-2613649718.html |website=Its a Southern Thing |access-date=January 17, 2022}}</ref> The home consisted of six bedrooms, 13 bathrooms, two kitchens, five fire places and a helicopter landing pad. It has been considered to be the largest log cabin home in the world.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheckler Finch |first1=Jackie |title=Travel: A visit to the largest log cabin in the world |url=https://www.daily-journal.com/life/travel/travel-a-visit-to-the-largest-log-cabin-in-the-world/article_a1399b05-2193-598a-86d2-eea6ec091885.html |access-date=January 17, 2022 |work=[[Daily Journal (Illinois)|Daily Journal]] |date=April 16, 2011}}</ref><ref name="Forbes">{{cite journal |title=Barbara Mandrell's Quaint Log Cabin |journal=[[Forbes]] |date=May 17, 2002 |url=https://www.forbes.com/2002/05/17/0517how1.html?sh=19bec3016aa0 |access-date=January 17, 2022}}</ref> Mandrell sold the home in 2002 in order to downsize. The home was auctioned.<ref name="Forbes"/> It has since been turned into a tourist attraction with a restaurant, a hotel, an outdoor music venue, and an indoor [[shooting range]].<ref name="behindthescenesatfontanel">{{Cite news|last=Stivender|first=Knight|date=September 16, 2012|title=Behind the scenes at Fontanel: Barbara Mandrell's former home finds new groove as entertainment mecca|url=http://archive.tennessean.com/article/20120916/LIFE01/309160022/Behind-scenes-Fontanel|newspaper=The Tennessean |access-date=September 3, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=April 2017|bot=medic}}{{Cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name="aboutnashville">{{Cite web|url=http://nashville.about.com/od/tourism/a/fontanelmansion.htm|first=Jan|last=Duke|title=Fontanel Mansion: Exploring the Fontanel Mansion & Farm|website=[[Dotdash|About.com]]|access-date=September 3, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907194840/http://nashville.about.com/od/tourism/a/fontanelmansion.htm|archive-date=September 7, 2015}}</ref> Her daughter Jaime was the human resources manager of the mansion until February 2017. She then began a new career with a company that works to place people with addiction issues into appropriate rehabilitation facilities.<ref name="behindthescenesatfontanel" /><ref>{{Cite web|title=Let's Catch Up: July 26, 2017|url=http://www.barbara-mandrell.com/blog/|publisher=barbara-mandrell.com|access-date=February 12, 2019|archive-date=March 16, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220316232544/http://www.barbara-mandrell.com/blog|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Car crash===
[[File:Jaguar XJ Vanden Plas 1986 (14630939895).jpg|thumb|right|On September 11, 1984, Mandrell and her two children were struck head-on by an oncoming car in Nashville, Tennessee. At the time of the crash, Mandrell was driving a [[Jaguar XJ]] sedan.|alt=A picture of a Jaguar XJ sedan, parked in front of a van]]
On September 11, 1984, Mandrell and her two children were involved in a head-on car collision near their Nashville home.<ref name="NY Times Car">{{cite news |title=Barbara Mandrell, 35, Singer, Injured in Fatal 2-Car Crash |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/09/12/us/barbara-mandrell-35-singer-injured-in-fatal-2-car-crash.html |access-date=January 18, 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 12, 1984}}</ref> The driver of the other car in the crash (19-year-old college student Mark White) was killed instantly.<ref name="Mandrell Injured in Auto Accident">{{Cite news|last1=Mandrell|first1=Barbara|title=Mandrell Injured in Auto Accident|work=The New York Times |date=September 12, 1984 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/09/12/us/barbara-mandrell-35-singer-injured-in-fatal-2-car-crash.html|access-date=April 9, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419224910/http://www.nytimes.com/1984/09/12/us/barbara-mandrell-35-singer-injured-in-fatal-2-car-crash.html|archive-date=April 19, 2015}}</ref> The police report stated that White's car had crossed the center line of the road, causing a head-on collision with Mandrell's [[Jaguar XJ]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}}<ref name="UPI">{{cite web |last1=Lewis |first1=Jim |title=Lawsuit puts Mandrell in hot water with fans |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1985/09/14/Lawsuit-puts-Mandrell-in-hot-water-with-fans/5172495518400/#:~:text=The%20suit%20accused%20White%20of,her%20husband%20and%20two%20children.&text=Harwell%20said%20Friday%20Mandrell%20and,do%20it%2C%27%20Harwell%20said. |website=UPI |access-date=January 31, 2021 |language=en |date=September 14, 1985}}</ref> Mandrell's children suffered only minor injuries and were released from the hospital shortly after their arrival.<ref name="NY Times Car"/> Mandrell suffered critical injuries from the crash.<ref name="NY Times Car"/> These injuries included a broken femur, shattered ankle, injured knee and a concussion resulting in temporary brain damage.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}}

Mandrell's injuries from the crash resulted in her suffering from pain throughout her body for months.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} Much of the physical pain she suffered came from knee injuries. "You can't say she's in terrible pain all the time if the pain she's in is the kind where she's trying to exceed what that knee will do, trying to make it do its full thing again. Every day she's trying to make it exceed what it did the day before so she can finally get it back to full capacity," said father Irby Mandrell to the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hurst |first1=Jack |title=MANDRELL'S HEALING FINE, BUT THANKS TO DAD, SHE'S STILL HIGH PROFILE |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-01-06-8501010893-story.html |access-date=January 18, 2022 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=January 6, 1985}}</ref>

As a result of Mandrell's head injuries, she had a temporary shift in personality and experienced memory loss.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} "I would refer to myself in the third person: 'That was her' or 'She did that' or 'You should have asked her. I can't do that'," she told ''[[The 700 Club]]''.<ref name="700 Club">{{cite web |last1=Wilcox |first1=Cheryl |title=Barbara Mandrell: Sweetness Through Suffering |url=https://www1.cbn.com/700club/barbara-mandrell-sweetness-through-suffering |website=[[The 700 Club]] |access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref> Mandrell's injuries took over a year to fully recover.{{sfn|Wolff|2000|p=444}} In an interview with ''[[Country Music Television|CMT]]'', she explained that her head injury took about three years to fully recover. She explained that she still suffers from pain in her ankle.<ref name="CMT Interview"/> 

Mandrell has credited seat belts for saving her and her children's lives. Prior to the day of the crash, Mandrell was not a seat belt user. However, minutes prior to the crash, she observed unbelted children playing around in the back of a moving car. Thinking this unsafe, she told her children to put on their seat belts and she would as well. <ref>{{cite news |last1=Egler |first1=Daniel |last2=Franklin |first2=Tim |title=MANDRELL TO SING OUT SUPPORT FOR BELT LAW |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1985-05-06-8501270916-story.html |access-date=January 18, 2022 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=May 6, 1985}}</ref><ref name="Get to the Heart">{{cite book |last1=Mandrell |first1=Barbara |last2=Vecsey |first2=George |title=Get to the Heart: My Story |date=1990 |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-0553292435}}</ref> After the crash, she campaigned and filmed television commercials that advocated for the use of seat belts in cars.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilker |first1=Deborah |title=TURNING POINT BARBARA MANDRELL HAS SURVIVED TRAGEDY TO COME BACK A STRONGER PERSON, SHE SAYS |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1991-02-22-9101090943-story.html |access-date=January 18, 2022 |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |date=February 22, 1991}}</ref> She campaigned for arthritis and organ donation.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=342}} Mandrell was made honorary chairman of the [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gayoso |first1=Jay |title=NATIONAL CAMPAIGN PUSHES SEAT-BELT USE |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1985-11-24-8502220683-story.html |access-date=January 18, 2022 |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |date=November 24, 1985}}</ref>

Nearly a year later, in accordance with Tennessee state law, Mandrell was required to sue the White family for $10.3 million in damages in order to collect from her own insurance company.<ref name="UPI lawsuit">{{cite news |title=Names in the News |url=https://apnews.com/article/82b649548014623d008974644676dfa5 |access-date=January 18, 2022 |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 14, 1985}}</ref><ref name="UPI"/> Her legal team contacted the White family to inform them that Mandrell did not want money from them but instead needed to do it for legal purposes. The lawsuit created controversy among Mandrell's fans. "I'm not blaming the public{{nbsp}}... I would have felt the way they felt", she commented in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hurst |first1=Jack |title=REHABBED CAREER |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1995-07-27-9507270021-story.html |access-date=January 18, 2022 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=July 27, 1995}}</ref><ref name="UPI lawsuit"/>

